post_cb({"31489351": {"CommentCount": "2", "ViewCount": "58", "CreationDate": "2015-07-18T08:38:12.597", "LastActivityDate": "2015-07-18T08:38:12.597", "Title": "How to understand variadic templates in c++11", "PostTypeId": "1", "Id": "31489351", "Score": "0", "Body": "<p>Sometimes we use\uff08. . .\uff09to indicate that a template or function parameter represents a pack.\nSometimes we get an pack expansion by putting (. . . ) to the right of the pattern.</p>\n<p>I am a little confused about this two occasions above.</p>\n<p>In C++ standard document\uff0814.5.3 item 4\uff09:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_31489351_31489351_0\">\"In a function parameter pack (8.3.5); the pattern is the\n  parameter-declaration without the ellipsis.\"</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>there\u2019s one example about this quote:</p>\n<pre><code>template&lt;typename ...T1&gt;\nvoid  f1(T1 ...t1)\n{\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>According to above description,for function parameter pack,the pattern is (T1 t1). So why can't i do somethig like that, i put (...) to the right of the pattern,then i can get the code below:</p>\n<pre><code>template&lt;typename ...T2&gt;\nvoid  f2(T2 ...t2...) // f2(T2 ...t2...) -&gt; f2((T2 ...t2)...)-&gt;f2((T2 t2)...)\n{\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>I confusedly think that the (...) after t2 could mean pack expansion which the the pattern is (T2 t2).Then i found the code compiled success in my vs2013.Wow, do I find some inspiration yet? </p>\n<p>I brazenly began a new attempt.</p>\n<p>There\u2019s another quote in C++ standard(14.5.3 item 4):</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_31489351_31489351_1\">\"In a template parameter pack that is a pack expansion (14.1): \u2014 if\n  the template parameter pack is a parameter-declaration; the pattern is\n  the parameter-declaration without the ellipsis;\"</p>\n</blockquote>\n<pre><code>template&lt;typename ...T3&gt;\nvoid  f1(T3 ...t3)\n{\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>According to description, for the template parameter T3, the pattern is (typename T3), so: </p>\n<pre><code>template&lt;typename ...T4...&gt; \nclass get_a_error; // template&lt;(typename ...T4)...&gt; -&gt; template&lt;(typename T4)...&gt;\n</code></pre>\n<p>Without (...) the pattern is (typename T4),so i put (...) to the right of the pattern,then i got an error.</p>\n<p>Finally,I fell into confusion.</p>\n", "Tags": "<templates><c++11><variadic-templates>", "OwnerUserId": "4622957", "AnswerCount": "0"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_31489351_31489351_0": {"section_id": 121, "quality": 0.8571428571428571, "length": 6}, "so_31489351_31489351_1": {"section_id": 121, "quality": 0.9230769230769231, "length": 12}}, "n3337": {"so_31489351_31489351_0": {"section_id": 116, "quality": 0.8571428571428571, "length": 6}, "so_31489351_31489351_1": {"section_id": 116, "quality": 0.9230769230769231, "length": 12}}, "n4659": {"so_31489351_31489351_0": {"section_id": 125, "quality": 0.8571428571428571, "length": 6}, "so_31489351_31489351_1": {"section_id": 125, "quality": 0.9230769230769231, "length": 12}}}});